  "local_port": 49894,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the penalty for driving without insurance in Texas?",
  "response": "In Texas, driving without insurance is a serious offense that can result in significant penalties. Here\u2019s what you could face if you are caught driving without valid auto insurance:\n\n1. **Fines**: \n   - First offense: A fine ranging from $175 to $350.\n   - Subsequent offenses: The fine increases to between $350 and $1,000.\n\n2. **Driver\u2019s License Suspension**: \n   - First offense: Your driver\u2019s license could be suspended for up to two years unless you can provide proof of insurance or financial responsibility (such as an SR-22).\n   - Subsequent offenses: The suspension period may be longer, depending on the circumstances.\n\n3. **Vehicle Impoundment**: \n   - Your vehicle may be impounded if you are caught driving without insurance.\n\n4. **Reinstatement Fees**: \n   - To reinstate your driver\u2019s license after a suspension, you will need to pay a reinstatement fee, which is typically $100 for a first offense and higher for subsequent offenses.\n\n5. **SR-22 Requirement**: \n   - In some cases, you may be required to file an SR-22 form with the Texas Department of Public Safety (DPS) as proof of financial responsibility. This form is typically required for a period of two years and can increase your insurance premiums significantly.\n\n6. **Additional Penalties**: \n   - If you are involved in an accident while driving without insurance, you may be held personally liable for damages, which could result in substantial financial consequences, including lawsuits.\n\n7. **Community Service**: \n   - In some cases, you may be required to complete community service hours as part of your penalty.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that Texas operates under a \"fault\" system for auto insurance, meaning that drivers are required to carry a minimum amount of liability insurance to cover damages they may cause to others in an accident. Texas also offers alternative options for proving financial responsibility, such as a surety bond or a deposit with the Texas Comptroller. However, driving without any form of financial responsibility is illegal and can lead to the penalties outlined above.\n\nTo avoid these penalties, ensure that you maintain valid auto insurance coverage that meets Texas\u2019s minimum liability requirements at all times.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
